ions, and Kierner situates the play in its broader historical and cultural contexts. An extensive introduction provides readers with a background on life and politics in the United States in 1787, when Americans were in the midst of nation-building. The book also features a section with selections from contemporary letters, essays, novels, conduct books, and public documents, which debate issues of the era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aArranged marriagevDrama. 0aBetrothalvDrama. 0aConduct of lifevDrama. 0aManners and customsvDrama. 0aMate selectionvDrama. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy18th centuryvSources. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aContrast.  aRepublic.  acreative.  aearly.  ageneral.  ahistory.  amanner.  amaterials.  apresent.  areaders.  astudents.  ateachers.  auser-friendly.  awitty.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814749371423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814749371/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK